It feels right to me because of how intertwined faith was with daily life to the Egyptians.
Everything they had was because of a narrow strip of fertile land to either side of the Nile, and everything tied back to the gods & goddesses. Doubly so for anyone that had a skill.

Perhaps in private they'd grumble about their respective masters, but they'd give over as things added up. Small omens would have them questioning whether their respective patrons were tipping the scales that a life was weighed on.
And that gives you an entry for side characters that support the comedy.
>"oh, anon, you know that X is always a sign from Ptah"
>"I know it is, but there's nothing between me and that-"

>because the real servants of the gods are your friends
>and they're going to have some fun first
